    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Decibels of Danger: The Noisy Subways</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Pierre C Haber letter, commenting on May 26 article on subway noise, says MTA should replace steel train wheels with rubber ones</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Screeching Won't Come to Halt'' (news article, May 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Screeching Won't Come to Halt'' (news article, May 26):</p>
        <p>The Metropolitan Transportation Authority should study and adapt the traction systems of Montreal, Paris and Mexico City: rubber-tired wheels glide silently on the steel rails. The Metro in Paris originally had steel wheels also, but it switched to rubber after World War II.</p>
        <p>PIERRE C. HABER  New York, May 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
